    "opinion": "As a 61-year-old carpenter living in New York, I've seen how things get built right or wrong, and that applies to social media too. I spend about an hour daily on platforms, mostly checking in with my four kids and sharing baking photos from my kitchen. When it comes to fake content, I take a practical approach. First, I don't share anything unless I'm sure it's true—like measuring twice before cutting wood. If something seems off, I check reliable sources like my local news station or church bulletin before believing it. My vocational training taught me that good work requires attention to detail, so I look closely at posts: who shared it, when, and why. Since I'm not very open to new experiences and prefer stability, I stick to familiar groups and pages I trust. My moderate neuroticism means I sometimes worry about misinformation affecting my family, especially my grandchildren who use social media more. But being low in agreeableness helps me question things rather than just going along. I've learned that fake content often plays on emotions, so I pause before reacting. My Christian beliefs guide me to seek truth and avoid spreading falsehoods. In my hobbies like cycling and running, I've met diverse people, reminding me that perspectives vary, so I consider multiple views. Ultimately, managing fake content is about being careful and responsible, just like in carpentry—using the right tools (critical thinking) and materials (verified information) to build a truthful online space.",
